Revenue recognition  - In May 2014, the FASB issued accounting guidance that provides a single, comprehensive revenue
recognition model for all contracts with customers and supersedes most of the existing revenue recognition requirements. Under this
guidance, an entity should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or servic es to customers in an amount that
reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. The Company adopted
this guidance effective January 1, 2018 under the modified retrospective transition method, applying the standard to contracts not
completed as of January 1, 2018 and considered the aggregate amount of modifications.
This revenue guidance impacts the timing of certain customer incentives recognized in the Company’ s consolidated statement of
operations, as they are recognized over the life of the contract. Previously , such incentives were recognized when earned by the
customer . This revenue guidance also impacts the Company’ s accounting recognition for certain market development fund
contributions and expenditures. Historically , these items were recorded on a net basis in net revenue and will now be recognized on
a gross basis, resulting in an increase to both revenues and expenses.
